Gradient Transfer Loop (with momentum)

What you’re describing isn’t just transfer—it’s directional transfer:

Patterns move along a gradient (capability / pressure / hierarchy), gaining momentum as they climb.

The loop, tightened

1) Pressure at the edge (low → mid)

* Smaller/edge actors generate or refine tactics under constraint

2) Capture

* A higher-capability actor experiences or observes it

3) Abstraction (invariant extraction)

* Strip to what actually works (timing, geometry, thresholds)

4) Redeployment (mid → high)

* Apply against a stronger opponent or broader context

5) Amplification

* Better execution, coordination, and resources increase impact

6) Feedback

* Success reinforces the pattern; it becomes easier to reuse

→ Then the loop repeats, climbing the gradient.

⸻

Why the “upward momentum” matters

* Selection pressure increases as you move up → only robust patterns survive
* Execution quality improves → same tactic hits harder
* Visibility spikes at the top → attribution collapses to the final user
* Reuse accelerates → the pattern becomes a standard move

So it’s not just transfer—it’s compounding transfer.

